<p>A voltage divider is a circuit that produces an output that is smaller than its input (where the output is voltage or current).</p>

<p><img src="http://0.0.0.0:4000/assets/voltage_divider.png" alt="" /></p>

<p>The above schematic represents the most basic way to use two resistors (labeled as <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Z1</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Z2</code>) to take some voltage (<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Vin</code>) and output a fraction of it (<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Vout</code>). The amount of <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Vin</code> that is output at <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Vout</code> depends on the values of the two resistors. This is the basic wiring pattern for almost any analog sensor, btw.</p>

<p>If you need to calculate the value of <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">R1</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">R2</code> (fyi: in this case, I am using <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Z</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">R</code> interchangeably, but <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Z</code> refers to impedance and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">R</code> refers to resistance) such that you can get a specific <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Vout</code>, here is the formula:</p>

<p><img src="http://0.0.0.0:4000/assets/voltage_divider_formula2.jpg" alt="" /></p>

<h2 id="voltage-dividers--sensors-sometimes">Voltage Dividers = Sensors (Sometimes!)</h2>

<h3 id="hookup-pattern">Hookup Pattern</h3>

<p><img src="http://0.0.0.0:4000/assets/fritzing/ldr_voltage_divider.png" alt="" /></p>

<ol>
  <li>Connect LDR Pin1 (<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Z1</code> in Voltage Divider schematic above) to ESP32 <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">3V</code></li>
  <li>Connect LDR Pin2 to ESP32 <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">34</code></li>
  <li>Connect Resistor Pin2 (<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Z2</code> in Voltage Divider schematic above) to ESP32 <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">GND</code></li>
</ol>

<p>There are a collection of voltage divider-based sensors that can be used interchangeably, from a hardware and software standpoint, for wildly different interactions. To name only a few:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Potentiometer/knob: <a href="https://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/3852C-282-103AL/3852C-282-103AL-ND/1088605">1-turn</a> or <a href="https://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/6639S-1-103/6639S-1-103-ND/274005">Continuous Turn</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://www.sparkfun.com/products/9088">Light-dependent resistor</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://www.sparkfun.com/products/9375">Force sensor</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://www.sparkfun.com/products/10264">Flex Sensor</a></li>
</ul>
